  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Port workers in Szczecin and southwestern coal miners today 08/17/1988 declared sympathy strikes with miners demanding the legalization of Solidarity.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   In support of 3,000 colleagues striking for a second day at the July Manifesto mine in Jastrzebie, workers at the nearby Morcinek mine launched their own occupation strike.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Workers at the nearby Borynia mine staged a brief sympathy rally but went back to work Tuesday 08/16/1988 afternoon.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Five strikes in Poland from 04/25/1988 to 05/10/1988, and brief stoppages or strike threats in 25 more work places, constituted the worst labor unrest in the country since the 1981 martial-law crackdown.
  </a>
